708583f-a.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 35th Street
708583f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, west side, south from 35th Street, showing
from left to right, the Caswell home (became the University
Club and which was remodelled in the Queen Anne style in 1887
for the New York Club), the A. T. Stewart home (became the
Manhattan Club in 1891), the twin Astor homes (removed separ-
ately for the Waldorf (in 1893) Astoria (about 1897) Hotel),
and the then dominant Marble Collegiate Church (erected 1851-4).
Absent in this view are two items that appear in slightly later
photos. These are the Fifth Avenue Art Galleries, a two story
structure, erected by the Caswell estate between their home and
the Stewart house, and the Hotel Cambridge at the S. W. corner
of 33rd Street.

708592f-a.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 35th Street
708592f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, north across 35th Street, showing an early
view of this arterial thoroughfare at the start of its transi-
tion from a residential nature to a business street. In the
center is the then dominant Brick Presbyterian Church at the
N. W. corner of 37th Street. The spires in the distance are
atop theChufch of the Divine Paternity (45th St.) and the
Collegiate Reformed Protestant Dutch Church (48th St.).
About 1890
